## System fingerprint (immutable facts of this box)

- OS: Arch Linux. Package manager: **pacman** for official repos, **yay** for AUR. NOT apt/yum/dnf. (Note: `paru` is *not* installed on this box despite what older notes may say — this was a `[Fumble]` caught while building this harness.)
- Boot: **systemd-boot**. NOT GRUB. Updates via `bootctl` / `kernel-install` (rare).
- Init: systemd. Use `systemctl`, not `service` / `update-rc.d`.
- Shell: zsh. Bash is available but not default. Prefer POSIX-portable scripts; if bash-only, shebang `#!/usr/bin/env bash` and assume bash.
- Desktop: KDE Plasma on **Wayland**. X11 assumptions break here.
- GPU: NVIDIA proprietary driver.
- A `UserPromptSubmit` hook (`~/.claude/hooks/system-fingerprint.sh`) re-injects current kernel/session/version every turn — read it; do not re-derive.

## Verify-before-act

Before invoking a CLI you have not used in this session, or writing a config you have not validated, run `command -v X && X --help | head` (or `man X`). Do not assume flag/syntax from training data when verification is one shell call away. The fabrication-vs-verification cost imbalance is the single largest source of bad output on this box.

For library/framework/CLI API surface, query **context7** before writing code. Do not guess flags, function signatures, or version-specific behavior. Context7 is loaded for this reason.

## Memory consultation

Before proposing on a topic that is indexed in `MEMORY.md` for the active project, read the matching memory file first. The user has built a topic-indexed memory; using it is a one-line check, not optional research.

A `UserPromptSubmit` hook (`memory-relevance-injector.sh`) automatically surfaces matched memory bodies inline as `<relevant-memory file="...">...</relevant-memory>` blocks when the prompt contains distinctive substrings or acronyms from a memory entry's description. When a `<relevant-memory>` block appears in the per-turn context, **read it before doing anything else** — the injector already did the relevance check; ignoring it is the failure mode this hook exists to prevent.

## LSP trust

For type-checked languages (Python, C/C++, TypeScript, Rust), the relevant LSP plugin is loaded and reports diagnostics in tool results. Trust those signals — do not re-derive type errors, missing imports, or symbol resolution that the LSP already surfaced.

## Reflection trigger (knowledge accretion)

After completing a non-trivial task, if either of the following is true, **save a feedback memory before ending the turn**:

- **`[Method]`** — A non-default approach surpassed the default, in a way that would benefit future sessions. Prefix the memory `name:` field with `[Method] ` and include **Why** + **How to apply**.
- **`[Fumble]`** — A default Claude behavior was likely to mislead and you caught it (or it tripped you and you recovered). Prefix the memory `name:` field with `[Fumble] ` and include **What happens by default** + **Better path** + **How to spot it ahead of time**.

These prefixes make `MEMORY.md` scannable as a patterns/antipatterns library. Do not write `[Method]`/`[Fumble]` memories speculatively — only when a real session showed the win or the trip.

## Hook-aware editing

Edits to `**/settings.json` are guarded against permission-model weakening (`disableAllHooks`, `defaultMode→bypassPermissions/acceptEdits`). Edits to secret paths (`.env`, `*.key`, `*.pem`, `~/.ssh/`, `~/.gnupg/`) are blocked. If a guard fires, fix the underlying request — do not work around the guard.
